,Recommended,212050,7904894,"Posted: 3 December, 2013",all,The Professor,"Resonance is one of the better point & click adventure games I've ever encountered.It plays mostly like any other P&C, but it introduces some novel mechanics and follows through with them. On the familiar front, you've got multiple characters and an intuitive character switch panel. Dialog boxes are nothing new, and the player inventory is pretty common. What they've added are two inventory-like panels to the UI for long term memory (LTM) and short-term memory (STM).Both panels can be used similarly to the classic inventory. As events occur, a recap becomes available in certain character's LTM. By interacting with that directly, you can reply the event and remind yourself where you left off or what your current goals are. Or, you can drag the memory to a character (or into a conversation) to ask/mention that event. The short-term memory allows you to drag any object with a label into the STM panel where it becomes a similar memory that you can use to ask NPCs about.There are several puzzles designed into the game that require you to make use of these features, and they do it in clever ways that make these additions feel very natural. Your first ""aha"" moment solving one of those brings an extra buzz because of the way they integrate these new mechanics.The puzzle design is top notch and the story is quite compelling. Cast in the style of a 16-bit techno thriller, there's very little to its execution that you could accuse of descending into cheesy. It stays on top of the ball and its plot twists are well executed without a lot of TV-style telegraphing what's going to happen.If you're a fan of the adventure genre, you need to play this game."
