,Recommended,212050,3526013,"Posted: 4 October, 2012",all,[LUC] Chride,"If you, like all other PC gamers who grew up in the 90s, named your cat/dog/hamster Guybrush and hunted through numerous walkthroughs (from magazines, not the web, mind you!) to solve that one devlish puzzle, then you'll surely love ""Resonance"", a new indie-adventure title. A clear homage to the adventure genre of the 90's, Resonance also brings something new to the table; the ingenious use of multiple characters to solve complex puzzles (think Maniac Mansion/Day of the Tentacle) and the invention of ""long/short term memory"", ie an ability to use any object and event as a ""usable topic"". With this new approach, Resonance raises the bar for the genre and makes it that more complex and appealing. The story is complex enough to grab a hold of you and the puzzles make sense. So it's not just nostalgia that draws you to the game, although I do love the retro graphics, it is actually a very clever little game. If you're an adventure game buff, I suggest you try it out."
